Here's how to implement all three requirements:

## 1. Custom "Cancel" Back Button

In your `EditProductPage.xaml`, override the back button behavior:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

## 2 & 3. Navigation Guard with Confirmation Dialog

In `AppShell.xaml.cs`, override `OnNavigating` with a deferral for the async dialog:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop &&
        Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page &&
        page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm &&
        vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

## 3. ViewModel with CancelCommand

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task Cancel()
    {
        // This triggers OnNavigating, which shows the guard dialog
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is required for async checks â€” without it the navigation completes before your dialog returns.
- `args.Cancel()` stops the navigation if the user chooses "Stay".
- The `CancelCommand` simply calls `GoToAsync("..")`, which routes through the same guard logic.
